 # An Ecosystem for Shortening the Coming Darkness
 
 - Speaker intro
+  - Felicitas Pojtinger
+  - @pojntfx pretty much everywhere
+  - During the day I'm a distributed systems engineer who also works on low-level userspace
+  - During the night I work on Free Software projects
 - Background on what's going on
+  - Society is drowning in slop, ethics and competence are becoming liabilities, and each day the light of humanity seems to dim a bit more
+  - I can only really speak about the systems I know something about, but there are many others that are just as or more important (e.g. agriculture, healthcare etc.) that I won't be talking about today but there are many more competent folks in the group
+  - In tech, esp. since 2024 but also starting much earlier, a concentration of power the likes we've not seen before
+  - Simultaneously tech is becoming more and more inescapable, even just to pay for transit, to pay for food, to receive healthcare notifications, to file taxes and pretty much every core civic function, so "just not using it" is less than less of an option
+  - Since tech is one of the industries most centralized in the US, the US started to abuse this position of power more and more, and despite this almost all new software is fully dependent on the US
+  - Children get forced into US systems from school and onwards, it's impossible to even pay for food without approval from a US company, and even systems necessary for core civic society to function (e.g. messaging in parliaments) have kill switches for the US built in now
+  - Example of this happening: Karim Asad Ahmad Khan, ICC prosecutor, got sanctioned by the US for fighting the genocide in Gaza and couldn't communicate with his colleagues via email anymore since the ICC had a dependency on US software
+  - As a result, esp. in Europe, a growing movement of digital sovereignty is developing
+  - The idea is not just that data stays inside of national borders under local laws, but software that "supports the ability of a nation or individual to be able to exercise control over and continue to maintain and use the systems they rely on even if the cables under the ocean are cut and the airwaves are jammed by a foreign adversary"
+  - Examples are the EU hosting their own sovereign social media (Mastodon, on the fediverse), the Netherlands adopting their own sovereign software forge (Forgejo, also on the fediverse), the French government and more and more German states switching to Linux for public institutions, and the German government making the open ODT format instead of the proprietary Word docx format mandatory, and most EU countries now using the sovereign, federated, encrypted Matrix protocol for all communication and LibreOffice for all documents, esp. in the military
+  - Democracies everywhere on the planet are fighting to remove US influence and kill switches on digital spaces from civic society in a way that has never been as present as this before
+  - Usually this focuses on formats and servers, which is good, but for technology to be more resilient I think we need to go one step further and focus on our personal computing tools - phones, tablets, laptops, TVs, routers, printers, etc. - too
 - Groups that are fighting back and how
+  - Many organizations are working on fighting back on this, esp. for personal computing devices, but the most interesting one in my opinion is the Modal Collective
+  - (I am not affiliated with the Modal Collective)
 - Goals
 - Principles
 - A stack of emancipatory software
